% Automatisch generiert — Thema: Cloning
% arg/1 Fakten
arg(pro29).  % [pro] Because of their plasticity, embryonic stem cells can be manipulated to become any cell in the human body, e.g., neural cells, retinal cells, liver cells, pancreatic cells, or heart cells.
arg(pro7).  % [pro] Two gay women could use this technology to conceive a child of their own using their individual 23 chromosomes.
arg(pro58).  % [pro] At least two religions, the Raelian Religion and the Summum Religion, believe in cloning as one of their tenets.
arg(pro36).  % [pro] The speaker(s) are not saying that a clone would be a carbon copy with no individuality.
arg(pro27).  % [pro] Reproductive cloning can provide genetically related children for people who cannot be helped by other fertility treatments (i.e., who do not produce eggs or sperm).
arg(con140).  % [con] Cloned people would not have full rights.
arg(con140b).  % [con] Cloned people are just copies.
arg(con140c).  % [con] A lot of people worry that cloned people would not have full rights.
arg(con23).  % [con] Creating a child for the sole purpose of saving another child violates the formula of humanity.
arg(con23b).  % [con] The child is created specifically for the purpose of saving another child.
arg(con152).  % [con] Evidence suggests that clones often have built-in genetic defects.
arg(con152b).  % [con] Evidence suggests that clones are unhealthy.
arg(con152c).  % [con] Evidence suggests that genetic defects and poor health in clones can lead to premature ageing and even death.
arg(con109).  % [con] Would there be any defense against people collecting cells and cloning random people?
arg(con9).  % [con] Ian Wilmut, Dolly’s creator, has denounced human reproductive cloning as too dangerous to attempt (Travis, 2001).
arg(con8).  % [con] Cloning could create new societal division.
arg(con8b).  % [con] Perfect clones would be treated in a different way than naturally born people.
arg(con24).  % [con] Cloning would result in a lack of uniqueness.
arg(con24b).  % [con] Cloning would violate convictions regarding human individuality and freedom.

% att/2 Fakten  (Dung 1995 — binär; Typ/conf aus LLM-Kandidaten als Kommentar)
att(con152b, pro29).  % [undercutting] conf=80 — Evidence that clones are unhealthy challenges the claim that stem‑cell plasticity makes cloning beneficial.
att(con152c, pro29).  % [undercutting] conf=80 — Reports of genetic defects and premature ageing in clones undermine the positive implication of stem‑cell plasticity.
att(con9, pro29).  % [undercutting] conf=70 — Wilmut’s denunciation of human cloning as dangerous questions the practical value of stem‑cell plasticity.
att(con152, pro7).  % [undermining] conf=70 — Asserts clones often have genetic defects, challenging the premise that cloning can produce a viable child for gay women.
att(con152b, pro7).  % [undermining] conf=70 — Claims clones are unhealthy, undermining the feasibility premise of pro7.
att(con152c, pro7).  % [undermining] conf=75 — Points to severe health problems in clones, further undermining the premise that cloning can yield a healthy child.
att(pro7, con9).  % [rebuttal] conf=88 — Pro7 claims cloning can be used beneficially, which contradicts Con9’s claim that cloning is too dangerous to attempt.
